<DOC><DOCNO> AP880804-0042 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1233EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w BC-Congress-Convictions 1stLd-Writethru a0604 08-04 0738</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Congress-Convictions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,0750</SECOND><HEAD>Biaggi 12th Lawmaker In Decade To Be Convicted Or Plead Guilty</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT Biaggi to Democrat sted Republican</NOTE><HEAD>With PM-Biaggi-Wedtech</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., found guiltyThursday of all but one of 16 counts including conspiracy,extortion, tax evasion and receiving bribes in the Wedtechcorruption scandal, is the 12th member of congress to be convictedof criminal charges or plead guilty to them during the past decade.   Biaggi, 70, also was convicted Sept. 22, 1987, of obstructingjustice, accepting a gratuity, and illegal interstate travel in acase involving charges he had accepted paid vacations from a formerleader of the Brooklyn Democratic Party. Biaggi was acquitted ofmore serious bribery and conspiracy charges.   The 10-term Bronx congressman was the 15th federal lawmaker tobe indicted over the past decade, and the second one indicted in1987.   The other congressman to be indicted in 1987, Rep. Harold E.Ford, D- Tenn., was charged in April of last year with bank, mailand tax fraud.   Other members of Congress indicted since early 1977:   _Rep. Charles C. Diggs Jr., D-Mich., was indicted in March 1978and convicted in October 1978 on 29 felony counts of illegallydiverting his congressional employees' salaries to his personaluse. Censured by the House in 1979, Diggs resigned from Congress in1980 and served seven months of a three-year prison sentence.   _Rep. Daniel J. Flood, D-Pa., was indicted in the fall of 1978on 13 counts of bribery, conspiracy and perjury. His trial on 11counts ended in mistrial in February 1979, and he resigned from theHouse in January 1980 for health reasons, after the House ethicscommittee had accused him of 25 violations of House rules. InFebruary 1980, he pleaded guilty to conspiracy, in aplea-bargaining arrangement, and was given a year's probation.   _Rep. Joshua Eilberg, D-Pa., was indicted in October 1978 onfederal charges of illegally receiving compensation to help aPhiladelphia hospital get a $14.5 million federal grant. He pleadedguilty in February 1979 and was sentenced to five years' probationand fined $10,000.   _Rep. Claude ``Buddy'' Leach, D-La., was indicted in July 1979on charges of buying votes in the 1978 elections, and was accusedof violating federal campaign finance laws. He was acquitted ofsome vote-buying counts and the others were dropped, and a courtdismissed the charges of campaign finance law violations.   _Sen. Harrison Williams Jr., D-N.J., was convicted in May 1981on charges stemming from the FBI's Abscam investigation, includingconspiracy, bribery, conflict of interest, receiving an unlawfulgratuity and interstate travel in aid of a racketeering enterprise.   Williams resigned from the Senate in March 1982. He was paroledfrom a Newark, N.J., halfway house in January 1986 after servingnearly two years of a three-year sentence at the federalpenitentiary at Allenwood, Pa.   Six House members also were indicted as a result of theundercover Abscam investigation, and all served prison terms. Theywere:   Rep. Raymond Lederer, D-Pa., was convicted in January 1981 ofconspiracy, bribery, receiving an unlawful gratuity and interstatetravel to further racketeering; Rep. Michael Myers, D-Pa., wasconvicted in August 1980 of conspiracy, bribery and interstatetravel; Rep. John Jenrette, D-S.C., was convicted in October 1980of sharing a $50,000 bribe.   Also, Rep. John Murphy, D-N.Y., was convicted in December 1980of conspiracy, conflict of interest and receiving an unlawfulgratuity; Rep. Frank Thompson, D-N.J., was convicted in December1980 of bribery, conspiracy and aiding and abetting in theacceptance of a criminal gratuity; Rep. Richard Kelly, R-Fla., wasconvicted in Januery 1981 of taking a $25,000 bribe from anundercover FBI agent and of taking part in a $250,000 briberyconspiracy.   _Rep. George Hansen, R-Idaho, indicted in April 1983 andconvicted one year later on charges of violating the 1978 Ethics inGovernment Act by failing to report $333,978 in loans and othertransactions on his financial disclosure forms. He surrendered June20, 1986, to begin serving a sentence of 5 to 15 months at thefederal correctional facility at Petersburg, Va., and was releasedon parole Dec. 19, 1986.   _Rep. Bobbi Fiedler, R-Calif., was indicted Jan. 23, 1986, alongwith aide on charges she tried to buy off an opponent for the GOPSenate nomination in California. The charges subsequently weredismissed by a Superior Court judge in Los Angeles, and she lostthe GOP primary.</TEXT></DOC>